#Class title

A Primer of Radio Interferometry
Miguel Pérez-Torres (torres@iaa.csic.es)
Instituto de Astrofísica de Andalucía - CSIC, Granada


At the end of this class, I hope you'll understand:
why radio interferometry is needed
what an interferometer measures
how those measurements become an image
why calibration and incomplete sampling matter.



#Slide 0 
Units

Astrophysicists normally use cgs 
Radio astronomers measure flux densities in Jy
Get used to convert cm to GHz and viceversa

cgs - centimeter, gram, second
1 Jy = 1E-23 erg/s/cm/Hz
Radio: from ~10 MHz up to ~100 GHz (submm)



# Slide 1
Why radio interferometry?

Radio wavelengths are long, so achieving 
high angular resolution with a 
single dish is very difficult.

#What to show

A simple comparison:
optical wavelength: ∼500 nm
radio wavelength: cm to m
θ ∼ λ / D

Interferometry - A solution to 
the angular-resolution problem

# VLA figure
